<TITLE> Journalist Borhan Ahmed dies </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 24 (bdnews24.com)Former executive editor of The Daily Janakantha Borhan Ahmed, 67, died on Thursday morning of a heart attack while taking a walk in Gulshan Park, his wife said. His family told bdnews24.com that his first namaj-e-janaza will be held in Gulshan Azad Mosque after the Zohr prayers and the second at the National Press Club. "He had gone for a walk in the morning. He died of a cardiac arrest at around 8:30am. Your 'Borhan Bhai' is no more," wife Gulshan Ara Ahmed said to bdnews24.com. The senior journalist was taken to United Hospital in Gulshan after the attack but the doctors declared him dead on arrival. Ahmed was the founding executive editor of Janakantha, a position he resigned recently and joined another daily waiting to be launched as the editor. He was the president of the Consumers Association of Bangladesh, a consumer rights group, for a long time. Ahmed took active part in the War of Independence, anti-autocracy movement of 1990 and all movements launched championing the freedom of the newspapers and embraced jail sentences. He was the founding editor of 'The Weekly Charampatra'. Born in Manikganj in1944, he started his journalistic career as a sub-editor with 'The Daily Azad". Borhan was awarded the Sher-e-Bangla Medal in 1994, Youth Society Medal, Adhunik Medal given away by the president in 1997, Dinesh Chandra Sen Medal-2002 (India) and a number of other honours and distinctions. Notable among his published works are Karagarer Dinguli, Bhinno Deshe, Ganotantrik Shashon Byabostha O BNP-Awami League-er Rajniti, Shamakaleen Premer Galpo and Ganotantrer Panch Bachhor. Ahmed is survived by wife, daughter Dr Rumana Ahmed, son Saddam Ahmed and countless well-wishers. BNP chairperson and opposition leader Khaleda Zia in a condolence message sympathised with his family. Besides, other senior BNP leaders and journalists also condoled the death of the veteran in separate messages. bdne
